{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"286a9156-ebbc-41de-b8e8-fb460e8848cd","content":"Here's the configuration for automatic crash dump collection with NativeAOT in Kubernetes:\n\n**Environment variables** — set on your container:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  # Enable automatic crash dump generation\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  # Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"\n  # Path to createdump (required for NativeAOT — no default runtime layout)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n  # Dump output path (%d = PID, %t = timestamp)\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%d.%t\"\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes** — add a writable volume and the `SYS_PTRACE` capability that `createdump` needs:\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: myapp\n      # ... your image, env from above ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: dump-volume\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: dump-volume\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi   # adjust to your expected dump size\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is mandatory — `createdump` uses `ptrace` to read process memory.\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** is required for NativeAOT since there's no standard runtime directory to discover it automatically.\n- **`emptyDir`** is fine for ephemeral collection; swap to a `PersistentVolumeClaim` if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- Use **`sizeLimit`** — full dumps can be large; size it to at least your container's memory limit.\n- `%d` (PID) and `%t` (timestamp) in the dump name prevent overwrites across multiple crashes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"820c463d-f06d-479e-8422-160cbd92cf0e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty. The user is asking me to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app in Kubernetes. Let me provide the guidance based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics and Kubernetes.\n\nFor NativeAOT .NET apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps:\n\n1. NativeAOT doesn't use the same `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variables that CoreCLR uses\n2. For NativeAOT, you need to use OS-level mechanisms or configure the `createdump` tool differently\n\nActually, let me reconsider. \n\nStarting with .NET 8, NativeAOT does support crash dumps through environment variables. The main ones I need to focus on are `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to turn on mini dump collection, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify what kind of dump to capture, and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` to set where the dumps get written. There's also `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` for enabling diagnostics output from the createdump tool itself, and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpPath` for the directory path.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how NativeAOT handles this differently. NativeAOT bundles crash dump generation directly into the runtime on some platforms, but since the user has createdump at a custom location, I need to account for that. The environment variables like `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName`, and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` all work with NativeAOT since .NET 8, and there's also `DOTNET_EnableCrashReport` for generating text-based crash reports. The tricky part is that NativeAOT doesn't follow the standard runtime layout, so specifying the createdump tool path becomes necessary.\n\nFor the Kubernetes setup, I need to configure environment variables to enable crash dumps, set up a volume mount for storing the dump files, add the `SYS_PTRACE` capability since createdump requires ptrace access, and point to the custom createdump location. I should also think about dump file naming to include timestamps or PIDs to prevent overwrites, and for NativeAOT specifically, use `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` to reference the createdump binary.","outputTokens":1243,"requestId":"D816:1E62:2976CEB:2DCC7A4:69FBEFE8"},"id":"385b1963-67cc-4d28-9241-760f372983fd","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:50:57.021Z","parentId":"4560d11c-489c-4525-8dab-1cbd95453684"}
